R Notebook Analysing Stroke Data

PHS Scottish Stroke Statistics

This notebook contains explorative analysis and visualisations of stroke incidence and mortality data across Scotland.

  • Raw datasets are from PHS open data accessible via: https://www.opendata.nhs.scot/dataset/scottish-stroke-statistics

  • The raw datasets have been cleaned and saved within the folder ../clean_data/ the cleaned datafiles will be used and analysed here.

  • Data exploration, analysis and visualisations are covered in this notebook.

Note: this notebook and its visualisations are not exhaustive, not all types of visualisations/analysis are covered.

Other analysis types covered in separate notebooks:

For the analysis and construction of the predictive model please check the notebook: modelling_stroke_data.Rmd

For the clustering analysis, please check the notebook: clustering_stroke_data.Rmd

For the spatial analysis, creating a map with leaflet, please check the notebook: analysing_spatial_stroke_data.Rmd

crude rate and easr Two columns in all PHS open data files are of interest for data visualisation:

crude rate: The crude rate is the population-standardised rate of the event (here: incidences or mortality rate) Crude rate is the number of events per 100.000 people

EASR: is the The European Age-Sex Standardised Rate per 100,000 population. The numbers of deaths per 100 000 population are influenced by the age distribution of the population. For standardisation the European Standard Population (ESP) is used to standardise on age and sex.

Visualisations - are organised per data file / topic

  • 3a = stroke activity per HB
  • 3b = stroke mortality per HB
  • 3c = mortality per simd (Scottish Index Multiple Deprivation)
  • 4a = stroke activity per HB - demographics
  • 4b = stroke mortality per HB - demographics
  • 5 = Stroke mortality and incidences per health board
  • 6 = Percentage change in incidence and mortality rates for period 2012-2021 for major demographics

3A. General insights Stroke activity per HB

What is the number of total stroke incidences in Scotland per year from 2012 to now?

activity_hb %>% 
  select(financial_year, hbr, age_group, sex, admission_type, diagnosis, number_of_discharges, crude_rate, easr) %>% 
  filter(age_group == "All",
         admission_type == "All",
         sex == "All",
         hbr == "S92000003") %>% 
  group_by(financial_year) %>% 
  summarise(total_stroke_incidences = sum(number_of_discharges)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = financial_year, y = total_stroke_incidences) +
  geom_line(aes(group = 1), colour = "indianred", size = 2) +
  theme_light() +
  labs(
    x = "\nYear", 
    y = "Total incidences",
    title = "Total Cerebrovascular Disease Incidences per Year\n"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 70000))

Data/graph shows the total number of stroke incidences in Scotland over the years 2012/13 - 2021/22. We see an initial increase until 2016 after incidence rates are more stable.

However this gives the absolute number of incidences, which are not standardised for age and sex composition differences in the population across years. Standardisation is important in order to enable comparison between different areas and demographics.

What is the number of total stroke incidences split per diagnosis type?

plot_diagnosis_incidences <- activity_hb %>% 
  select(financial_year, hbr, age_group, sex, admission_type, diagnosis, number_of_discharges, crude_rate, easr) %>% 
  filter(age_group == "All",
         admission_type == "Emergency",
         sex == "All",
         hbr == "S92000003") %>% 
  mutate(diagnosis = recode(diagnosis, "TIAs and related syndromes" = "TIA")) %>% 
  mutate(financial_year = recode(financial_year, "2012/13" = "2012",
                                "2013/14" = "2013",
                                "2014/15" = "2014",
                                "2015/16" = "2015",
                                "2016/17" = "2016",
                                "2017/18" = "2017",
                                "2018/19" = "2018",
                                "2019/20" = "2019",
                                "2020/21" = "2020",
                                "2021/22" = "2021")) %>% 
  group_by(financial_year, diagnosis) %>% 
  summarise(total_incidences_easr = sum(easr)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = financial_year, y = total_incidences_easr, fill = diagnosis) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  theme_light(base_size = 15) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1), 
        legend.position = "none",
        legend.text = element_text(size = 10)) +
  labs(
    x = "\nYear", 
    y = "incidence rate per 100k population",
    title = "Cerebrovascular Disease",
    subtitle = "age and sex adjusted incidence rates per year"
  ) +
   scale_fill_manual(
    values = c(
      "Cerebrovascular Disease" = "indianred",
      "Stroke" = "springgreen3",
      "Subarachnoid Haemorrhage" = "springgreen4",
      "TIA" = "darkgreen")
    )

Graph shows the number of stroke incidences (age-sex standardised) in Scotland over the years 2012/13 - 2021/22 divided for diagnosis type. Majority of cases are diagnosed as Cerebrovascular disease, as expected since all types are classified as Cerebrovascular Disease. Stroke is the most common diagnosed type of CD.

Small number of cases are diagnosed as TIA, followed by Subarachnoid Haemorrhage. We see an initial increase until 2016 after incidence rates are more stable. Largest differences are found in Stroke, while TIA and Subarachnoid Haemorrhage are relatively stable across all years.

The first graph shows the age-sex standardised mortality rate due to Cerebrovascular Disease, and its most common diagnosis types, in Scotland over the year 2012-2021. Majority of deaths are diagnosed as strokes. Only a minority is caused by Subarachnoid haemorrhage.

The second graph introduces an additional layer/ split by age group. We observe that people aged 75+ are most commonly dying from Cerebrovascular Disease and all of its types. The data is age-sex standardised and we can therefore comapre the data. In total 600 per 100k people that are 75+ die from CD, while this is 100 per 100k or less for all remaining age groups.
